<emphasis box="[806,952,850,871]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="355">Distribution:</emphasis>
<collectingCountry box="[972,1066,850,871]" name="Curaçao" pageId="6" pageNumber="355">Curaçao</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Marcus Er &amp; Marcus Ev" box="[1094,1409,850,872]" pageId="6" pageNumber="355" pagination="1 - 129" refId="ref11030" refString="Marcus Er, Marcus Ev. 1970. Opisthobranchs from Curacao and faunistically related regions. Studies on the Fauna of Curacao and Other Caribbean Islands 33: 1 - 129." type="journal article" year="1970">Marcus &amp; Marcus, 1970</bibRefCitation>
); 
<collectingCountry box="[806,914,881,903]" name="Barbados" pageId="6" pageNumber="355">Barbados</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Edmunds M &amp; Just H" box="[934,1216,881,903]" pageId="6" pageNumber="355" pagination="185 - 203" refId="ref10302" refString="Edmunds M, Just H. 1983. Eolid nudibranchiate Mollusca from Barbados. Journal of Molluscan Studies 49: 185 - 203." type="journal article" year="1983">Edmunds &amp; Just, 1983</bibRefCitation>
); Cayman Island (
<bibRefCitation author="Hess DF &amp; Abbott RT &amp; Hamann J &amp; Meyer K &amp; Millen S &amp; Gosliner T &amp; Sefton N &amp; Hanlon RT" box="[814,1010,911,934]" pageId="6" pageNumber="355" pagination="139 - 189" refId="ref10646" refString="Hess DF, Abbott RT, Hamann J, Meyer K, Millen S, Gosliner T, Sefton N, Hanlon RT. 1994. Marine molluscs of the Cayman Islands. In: MA Brunt, JE Davies, eds. The Cayman Islands: natural history and biogeography. Monographiae Biologicae, No. 71. Dordrecht (The Netherlands): Kluwer Academic Publishers, 139 - 189." type="book chapter" year="1994">
Hess 
<emphasis box="[880,928,911,933]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="355">et al</emphasis>
., 1994
</bibRefCitation>
); 
<collectingCountry box="[1032,1139,911,933]" name="Bahamas" pageId="6" pageNumber="355">Bahamas</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Redfern C" box="[1156,1322,911,934]" pageId="6" pageNumber="355" refId="ref11182" refString="Redfern C. 2001. Bahamian seashells: a thousand species from Abaco, Bahamas. Boca Raton, FL: BahamianSeashells. com, Inc." type="book" year="2001">Redfern, 2001</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<caption pageId="6" pageNumber="355" startId="6.[144,223,1121,1140]" targetBox="[152,752,201,1087]" targetPageId="6">
<paragraph blockId="6.[144,759,1121,1229]" pageId="6" pageNumber="355">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[144,248,1121,1141]" pageId="6" pageNumber="355">Figure 5.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authorityName="MARCUS &amp; MARCUS" authorityYear="1970" box="[260,468,1122,1141]" class="Gastropoda" family="Aeolidiidae" genus="Berghia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Nudibranchia" pageId="6" pageNumber="355" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="creutzbergi">
<emphasis box="[260,468,1122,1141]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="355">Berghia creutzbergi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. A, lateral view of a specimen, showing the arrangement of the cerata; scale bar = 1 mm. B, radular tooth (13-mm-long specimen, from Praia de Armação); scale bar = 100 Mm.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph blockId="6.[144,759,1288,1708]" pageId="6" pageNumber="355">
bear papillae. In the preserved state, a narrow longitudinal fold on the anterior face is present in each rhinophore. The bases of the rhinophores are very close, and have a white spot on the head below them. The cerata are organized in five pairs of horseshoeshaped arches (
<figureCitation box="[325,411,1441,1463]" captionStart="Figure 5" captionStartId="6.[144,223,1121,1140]" captionTargetBox="[152,752,201,1087]" captionTargetId="figure-526@6.[148,756,195,1092]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="Figure 5. Berghia creutzbergi. A, lateral view of a specimen, showing the arrangement of the cerata; scale bar = 1 mm. B, radular tooth (13-mm-long specimen, from Praia de Armação); scale bar = 100 Mm." pageId="6" pageNumber="355">Fig. 5A</figureCitation>
). The first group contains the largest number of cerata (about 14). The second arch contains ten cerata, and the number diminishes toward the posterior end. The cerata of the posterior groups are stouter than the anterior ones, and have pointed tips. The genital opening is located on the right side, in front of the first arch of cerata. The anus is situated inside the second arch. The whitish foot ends in a thin and translucent tail.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="6.[144,759,1758,1903]" pageId="6" pageNumber="355">
<emphasis box="[144,405,1758,1779]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="355">Internal morphology:</emphasis>
The radular formula is 18 ¥ 0. 1. 0. The arched teeth posses numerous denticles (
<figureCitation box="[223,308,1819,1842]" captionStart="Figure 5" captionStartId="6.[144,223,1121,1140]" captionTargetBox="[152,752,201,1087]" captionTargetId="figure-526@6.[148,756,195,1092]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="Figure 5. Berghia creutzbergi. A, lateral view of a specimen, showing the arrangement of the cerata; scale bar = 1 mm. B, radular tooth (13-mm-long specimen, from Praia de Armação); scale bar = 100 Mm." pageId="6" pageNumber="355">Fig. 5B</figureCitation>
). One large tooth has 35 denticles on each side. The central denticle is smaller, and on its sides larger and a smaller denticles are arranged
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="6.[806,1421,993,1045]" pageId="6" pageNumber="355">
<emphasis box="[806,883,993,1014]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="355">
<collectingCountry box="[806,877,993,1014]" name="Brazil" pageId="6" pageNumber="355">Brazil</collectingCountry>
:
</emphasis>
This is the first record of this species from 
<collectingCountry box="[806,876,1023,1045]" name="Brazil" pageId="6" pageNumber="355">Brazil</collectingCountry>
(Praia de Armação, Buzios, 
<collectingRegion box="[1212,1385,1023,1045]" country="Brazil" name="Rio de Janeiro" pageId="6" pageNumber="355">Rio de Janeiro</collectingRegion>
).
</paragraph>
